1
00:00:01,002 --> 00:00:03,204
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay, so once again, I'm Paulette Vander Kloot.

2
00:00:03,224 --> 00:00:07,307
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm the facilitator of this subcommittee meeting.

3
00:00:07,407 --> 00:00:14,233
[SPEAKER_04]: This subcommittee is a subcommittee of the Medford Charter Review Committee.

4
00:00:14,813 --> 00:00:24,982
[SPEAKER_04]: And the purpose of our particular subcommittee is to consider the organization of the Medford School Committee as it relates to reviewing the charter of the city of Medford.

5
00:00:26,263 --> 00:00:44,239
[SPEAKER_04]: And so I think this is our third subcommittee meeting and tonight we're going to go over some more interview feedback and we're going to make a list of various pros and cons of the different areas and continue our discussion.

6
00:00:49,023 --> 00:00:59,235
[SPEAKER_04]: I think we'll begin with the fact that Phyllis Morrison and I went and had a very nice discussion with the mayor.

7
00:00:59,476 --> 00:01:00,357
[SPEAKER_04]: Did I put that one first?

8
00:01:00,417 --> 00:01:00,677
[SPEAKER_04]: I did.

9
00:01:01,057 --> 00:01:03,681
[SPEAKER_04]: With Mayor Brianna Kern, Mungo Kern.

10
00:01:04,942 --> 00:01:06,002
[SPEAKER_04]: on February 7th.

11
00:01:06,643 --> 00:01:16,670
[SPEAKER_04]: And I'm going to, I sent out the notes today to the committee members, but since everybody doesn't have them, I'm going to read them into the record.

12
00:01:16,830 --> 00:01:26,877
[SPEAKER_04]: And Phyllis, then maybe at the end, if you have any other things you wanted to add, Phyllis and I did collaborate this afternoon, so hopefully I've been inclusive.

13
00:01:27,877 --> 00:01:28,698
[SPEAKER_04]: Just a little background.

14
00:01:28,738 --> 00:01:29,799
[SPEAKER_04]: Can I ask you a question?

15
00:01:30,259 --> 00:01:30,439
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

16
00:01:31,100 --> 00:01:31,500
[SPEAKER_03]: Would it be,

17
00:01:32,723 --> 00:01:37,345
[SPEAKER_03]: more advantageous to share your screen with the notes and then read them also?

18
00:01:38,785 --> 00:01:40,546
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't know how to do that, Phyllis.

19
00:01:41,226 --> 00:01:54,130
[SPEAKER_01]: Actually, Paulette, I put them all in our shared drive, so I could probably, if I can do it right, pull it up from the shared drive.

20
00:01:55,327 --> 00:01:57,749
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay, so why don't you see if you can do that?

21
00:01:57,789 --> 00:01:58,869
[SPEAKER_04]: And in the meantime, I'll start.

22
00:01:58,970 --> 00:01:59,530
[SPEAKER_04]: Is that okay?

23
00:02:00,931 --> 00:02:02,412
[SPEAKER_03]: Have you made Eunice a co-host?

24
00:02:03,072 --> 00:02:03,393
[SPEAKER_03]: I have.

25
00:02:03,973 --> 00:02:04,954
[SPEAKER_03]: Good, then she's okay.

26
00:02:04,974 --> 00:02:06,675
[SPEAKER_03]: She can share the screen once she gets there.

27
00:02:08,256 --> 00:02:09,397
[SPEAKER_04]: I can figure out how to do it.

28
00:02:09,797 --> 00:02:11,298
[SPEAKER_04]: I'll make you a co-host too.

29
00:02:11,778 --> 00:02:12,299
[SPEAKER_04]: I've got it.

30
00:02:13,474 --> 00:02:19,741
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay, so Mayor Brianna Lungo-Kern is at the beginning of her third two-year term.

31
00:02:20,381 --> 00:02:23,945
[SPEAKER_04]: Previously, Brianna served as a member of the Medford City Council.

32
00:02:24,546 --> 00:02:28,970
[SPEAKER_04]: She was first elected in 2001 and served for 18 years, i.e.

33
00:02:29,090 --> 00:02:32,594
[SPEAKER_04]: nine terms, before being elected to mayor in 2001.

34
00:02:35,172 --> 00:02:45,001
[SPEAKER_04]: Mayor Lungo Kern greeted us warmly and extended her thanks and appreciation to the whole Charter Review Committee for undertaking this important initiative.

35
00:02:45,021 --> 00:02:46,762
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm sorry, Paula.

36
00:02:46,822 --> 00:02:48,724
[SPEAKER_06]: Can you make me co-host as well?

37
00:02:50,425 --> 00:02:51,006
[SPEAKER_04]: Is that Aubrey?

38
00:02:52,727 --> 00:02:52,968
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes.

39
00:02:53,488 --> 00:02:53,828
[SPEAKER_04]: OK.

40
00:02:54,048 --> 00:02:55,350
[SPEAKER_04]: I did, and then you went out.

41
00:02:55,950 --> 00:02:56,631
[SPEAKER_04]: So we'll do it again.

42
00:02:56,791 --> 00:02:57,231
[SPEAKER_04]: There you go.

43
00:02:58,512 --> 00:02:58,612
[SPEAKER_04]: OK?

44
00:03:02,378 --> 00:03:05,500
[SPEAKER_04]: And she greeted us warmly.

45
00:03:05,520 --> 00:03:07,501
[SPEAKER_04]: There we go.

46
00:03:07,801 --> 00:03:14,204
[SPEAKER_04]: Now, the funny enough thing is I can't read that at all, so I will continue to read off my paper.

47
00:03:14,364 --> 00:03:15,225
[SPEAKER_01]: Aubrey, you have it up?

48
00:03:16,327 --> 00:03:16,967
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes, she does.

49
00:03:17,508 --> 00:03:18,208
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay, never mind.

50
00:03:19,368 --> 00:03:19,769
[SPEAKER_01]: That's better.

51
00:03:19,809 --> 00:03:22,730
[SPEAKER_04]: We began our conversation with the question of term limits.

52
00:03:23,230 --> 00:03:32,515
[SPEAKER_04]: Brianna told us she had reviewed the tape of the previous Charter Committee meeting and was happy to see that the committee had voted to recommend term limits for the mayor.

53
00:03:33,235 --> 00:03:36,917
[SPEAKER_04]: She said she would have been happy with either a 12 or 16-year mandate.

54
00:03:37,617 --> 00:03:45,541
[SPEAKER_04]: Her preference for term limits for the mayor's position comes from her frustration in earlier years with the then long-serving mayor.

55
00:03:46,570 --> 00:03:55,973
[SPEAKER_04]: We went on to discuss the term length, and the mayor expressed a favorable opinion regarding the suggestion of a four-year length of term for the mayor's position.

56
00:03:56,794 --> 00:04:01,095
[SPEAKER_04]: It's hard to get a lot done in two years, and the election cycle takes a lot of time and energy.

57
00:04:01,896 --> 00:04:07,538
[SPEAKER_04]: Brianna is a little uncertain how a four-year term would feel, but believes a longer term would be beneficial.

58
00:04:08,483 --> 00:04:18,692
[SPEAKER_04]: As we discussed the various pros and cons, the mayor strongly expressed support for the idea of three-year terms for all office holders.

59
00:04:19,453 --> 00:04:21,955
[SPEAKER_04]: Could three-year terms be possible in Medford?

60
00:04:22,596 --> 00:04:29,842
[SPEAKER_04]: While she did not know the answer, the mayor hoped our committee would further explore this to see if it would be a possibility.

61
00:04:30,703 --> 00:04:36,849
[SPEAKER_04]: If the mayor's term was three years, she suggested that the term limit might be 15 years.

62
00:04:37,449 --> 00:04:42,554
[SPEAKER_04]: Brianna was undecided about term limits for both city council and school committee members.

63
00:04:43,675 --> 00:04:47,698
[SPEAKER_04]: We discussed ward versus at-large representation for the school committee.

64
00:04:48,399 --> 00:04:51,342
[SPEAKER_04]: Some combination might be preferable in ward

65
00:04:52,825 --> 00:04:58,108
[SPEAKER_04]: if wards could be combined and then additional at-large members elected as well.

66
00:04:58,828 --> 00:05:01,230
[SPEAKER_04]: The size of the committee is a consideration.

67
00:05:01,850 --> 00:05:05,552
[SPEAKER_04]: Could meetings become less effective with too many members vying to speak?

68
00:05:06,433 --> 00:05:13,377
[SPEAKER_04]: The mayor reminded us that sometimes it has been challenging to get people to run for school committee due to the large commitment of time.

69
00:05:14,097 --> 00:05:16,762
[SPEAKER_04]: She wouldn't want to discourage people who are interested.

70
00:05:17,323 --> 00:05:23,995
[SPEAKER_04]: On the flip side, she understands the drive for possibly being more inclusive by incorporating ward representation.

71
00:05:24,776 --> 00:05:26,499
[SPEAKER_04]: Would combining wards be a solution?

72
00:05:27,590 --> 00:05:33,934
[SPEAKER_04]: At first, the mayor admitted it was challenging to work all day and then go on to the school committee meetings.

73
00:05:34,174 --> 00:05:44,121
[SPEAKER_04]: However, once she got used to it, she enjoys her role and would definitely want to be on the school committee because she is well-versed in the scope of the needs of our students.

74
00:05:44,661 --> 00:05:46,843
[SPEAKER_04]: Her preference is for the mayor to chair the committee.

75
00:05:48,030 --> 00:05:48,830
[SPEAKER_04]: balance of power.

76
00:05:49,490 --> 00:05:55,031
[SPEAKER_04]: And this was really outside of the school committee issue, but she discussed this, so I wanted to include it.

77
00:05:55,831 --> 00:06:05,153
[SPEAKER_04]: The mayor and several city councilors have been working together to come up with a budget ordinance, which would provide to the city council quarterly budget documentation.

78
00:06:05,833 --> 00:06:14,955
[SPEAKER_04]: The mayor sees this joint agreement as a positive step in trying to set a more positive tone between the council and the mayor's office.

79
00:06:16,522 --> 00:06:21,664
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay, so that's really kind of the summation of our meeting with the mayor.

80
00:06:22,204 --> 00:06:23,864
[SPEAKER_04]: Phyllis, did you want to add anything else?

81
00:06:24,645 --> 00:06:31,787
[SPEAKER_03]: No, I think as you and I talked, you know, after the meeting and other times, I think that that really encapsulates everything she said.

82
00:06:32,247 --> 00:06:39,469
[SPEAKER_03]: I would like to say that she was very almost excited as we were at one of our last meetings about the possibility of a three-year term.

83
00:06:39,529 --> 00:06:40,810
[SPEAKER_03]: I think that's a pretty clear

84
00:06:44,787 --> 00:06:52,369
[SPEAKER_03]: point of view for a lot of us because the two-year terms are too short because you have to run every, I don't know, can it be possible?

85
00:06:52,449 --> 00:06:54,870
[SPEAKER_03]: Even the mayor's not sure about that, but she did.

86
00:06:54,970 --> 00:07:04,532
[SPEAKER_03]: One of the things I do want to share is that when we talked about three limits, you know, one of the questions that keeps coming up, will that be a presidential year, will it be a NAFTA year, be it this year?

87
00:07:04,992 --> 00:07:08,013
[SPEAKER_03]: But the other point is that she, you know, you know,

88
00:07:08,601 --> 00:07:10,222
[SPEAKER_03]: we can vote whenever we need to vote.

89
00:07:10,622 --> 00:07:12,263
[SPEAKER_03]: We have to look at what's best for the city.

90
00:07:12,643 --> 00:07:21,548
[SPEAKER_03]: And it's nice to know that all of these things are being talked about and discussed so we can get this charter to be most effective for our citizens.

91
00:07:22,874 --> 00:07:23,034
[SPEAKER_04]: Right.

92
00:07:23,094 --> 00:07:37,623
[SPEAKER_04]: I think my my takeaway was along the same lines is that in some ways, you know, I've heard this three year I've thought about the three year I've said to myself, oh, if only we could have three year terms and then sort of feeling like, oh, but it's probably impossible.

93
00:07:37,683 --> 00:07:40,985
[SPEAKER_04]: And there's an inequity between the election cycles.

94
00:07:41,025 --> 00:07:46,148
[SPEAKER_04]: But one of the things that Brianna says is it would be everybody would be having the same inequity.

95
00:07:46,708 --> 00:07:46,888
[SPEAKER_04]: Right.

96
00:07:47,108 --> 00:07:51,152
[SPEAKER_04]: So so she certainly encouraged us to look deeper and further.

97
00:07:51,672 --> 00:08:01,320
[SPEAKER_04]: And, you know, I don't really personally care if Medford is the only city in the Commonwealth who might say, hey, three years is the right length of term.

98
00:08:02,640 --> 00:08:07,281
[SPEAKER_04]: You know, and there are some others, they tend to be towns, they tend to have spring elections.

99
00:08:07,901 --> 00:08:12,902
[SPEAKER_04]: So we certainly, you know, it's really an area of discovery.

100
00:08:13,902 --> 00:08:16,923
[SPEAKER_04]: But anyway, I thought it was a very nice conversation.

101
00:08:17,623 --> 00:08:26,305
[SPEAKER_04]: And it was very exciting to talk to her and have her reflect on both the past and the future.

102
00:08:27,946 --> 00:08:29,468
[SPEAKER_04]: So that's that.

103
00:08:30,008 --> 00:08:32,711
[SPEAKER_03]: On a personal note for me, it cleared up a lot of things.

104
00:08:33,352 --> 00:08:43,864
[SPEAKER_03]: As someone who doesn't know that much about the school committee in Medfit, it was nice to talk to Maren, get her understanding and her information that she shared about the school committee with me also.

105
00:08:45,201 --> 00:08:48,061
[SPEAKER_03]: It was a very, very valuable interview for lots of reasons.

106
00:08:48,602 --> 00:09:03,804
[SPEAKER_04]: I think that she definitely felt like being on the school committee afforded her the opportunity to know more in depth about the school issues and that that was very, very important for her.

107
00:09:04,344 --> 00:09:05,024
[SPEAKER_04]: Very important.

108
00:09:05,284 --> 00:09:06,005
[SPEAKER_04]: Very important.

109
00:09:06,065 --> 00:09:06,245
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

110
00:09:06,925 --> 00:09:07,245
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay.

111
00:09:07,705 --> 00:09:07,965
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay.

112
00:09:08,185 --> 00:09:13,486
[SPEAKER_04]: Any questions about that interview or about our impressions of the interview?

113
00:09:14,346 --> 00:09:15,227
[SPEAKER_04]: Aubrey or Eunice?

114
00:09:16,268 --> 00:09:18,911
[SPEAKER_01]: One question, one thing that stood out to me, a couple of things.

115
00:09:18,971 --> 00:09:29,022
[SPEAKER_01]: First of all, I'm really glad that you were able to do that because I know she was interviewed with regards to the entire charter and her role as mayor.

116
00:09:29,763 --> 00:09:40,329
[SPEAKER_01]: You know, the, the, the entire scope, but I think honing in right on the school committee, I think was I'm really glad that we were able to get that done with her.

117
00:09:40,470 --> 00:09:43,031
[SPEAKER_01]: So, thanks to both of you for for that.

118
00:09:43,091 --> 00:09:45,272
[SPEAKER_01]: I think it was an important perspective.

119
00:09:45,292 --> 00:09:49,735
[SPEAKER_01]: 1 thing that struck me.

120
00:09:51,945 --> 00:09:59,971
[SPEAKER_01]: you know, is, she said, you know, getting people to run for school committee is hard because of the time commitment.

121
00:10:00,371 --> 00:10:04,414
[SPEAKER_01]: And I do remember a year, oh, I don't know, was it five or six elections ago?

122
00:10:04,434 --> 00:10:12,860
[SPEAKER_01]: Paula, you'll, you know, you're nodding, where nobody ran except for the six incumbents.

123
00:10:13,180 --> 00:10:14,061
[SPEAKER_01]: Right.

124
00:10:14,101 --> 00:10:20,826
[SPEAKER_01]: So my question would be is, is the time commitment for the school committee that much different than city council?

125
00:10:24,025 --> 00:10:27,946
[SPEAKER_04]: The time commitment for school committee is intense.

126
00:10:28,766 --> 00:10:37,709
[SPEAKER_04]: And you see people perceive that the school committee meets less because they have just two public meetings a month.

127
00:10:38,710 --> 00:10:47,153
[SPEAKER_04]: Just the two formal, while city council meets every Tuesday and school committee meets every Tuesday.

128
00:10:48,213 --> 00:10:50,015
[SPEAKER_04]: every other, twice a month.

129
00:10:50,455 --> 00:10:54,418
[SPEAKER_04]: So it seems like, oh, well, they have two less, but the amount of subcommittee meetings we have.

130
00:10:55,559 --> 00:11:09,230
[SPEAKER_04]: And I mean, so this past weekend, I saw a bunch of the new school committee members at the Medford Family Network Valentine's Day event.

131
00:11:09,910 --> 00:11:15,515
[SPEAKER_04]: And as is the tradition, the elected officials are asked to come and scoop ice cream.

132
00:11:16,403 --> 00:11:20,105
[SPEAKER_04]: And I looked at the new school committee members, and I said, well, how are you doing?

133
00:11:21,105 --> 00:11:27,027
[SPEAKER_04]: It was almost like there were deers in the headlights with their eyes circling around like a cartoon character.

134
00:11:27,567 --> 00:11:38,112
[SPEAKER_04]: And I know that Erica had put out saying, well, I've just spent, this is the end of my 40th hour working on school committee things this month.

135
00:11:38,212 --> 00:11:41,913
[SPEAKER_04]: Now, of course, she's new, and there's an awful lot.

136
00:11:45,073 --> 00:11:54,019
[SPEAKER_04]: Each one of them, in some way or another, expressed to me of saying that it was a lot to start out with.

137
00:11:54,439 --> 00:11:56,060
[SPEAKER_04]: It was very, very time consuming.

138
00:11:56,101 --> 00:12:05,567
[SPEAKER_04]: I see that Nicole Branley, another one of our new school committee members, has just arrived on scene, and she can probably attest to this, but it's a lot.

139
00:12:11,134 --> 00:12:11,874
[SPEAKER_04]: I had, yes.

140
00:12:12,174 --> 00:12:13,034
[SPEAKER_04]: Nicole, is that you?

141
00:12:13,634 --> 00:12:15,495
[SPEAKER_04]: It is, honey.

142
00:12:15,535 --> 00:12:17,656
[SPEAKER_04]: So am I portraying you accurately?

143
00:12:18,536 --> 00:12:20,737
[SPEAKER_04]: No, I think that was quite a good interpretation.

144
00:12:20,777 --> 00:12:21,157
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

145
00:12:23,358 --> 00:12:28,459
[SPEAKER_04]: So anyway, so a lot of what the school committee does is not really understood.

146
00:12:30,180 --> 00:12:36,762
[SPEAKER_04]: There were times many, many, many weeks when four out of five nights I was out doing school committee work.

147
00:12:37,262 --> 00:12:38,083
[SPEAKER_04]: And that might be

148
00:12:38,963 --> 00:12:42,845
[SPEAKER_04]: going to a student production, going to a subcommittee meeting.

149
00:12:44,265 --> 00:12:51,749
[SPEAKER_04]: Nicole and I talked the other day, and she was saying, whoa, there are six subcommittees, and I have to head one of them, and I'm on two other ones.

150
00:12:52,269 --> 00:12:53,529
[SPEAKER_04]: And how do I do?

151
00:12:54,130 --> 00:12:55,830
[SPEAKER_04]: So it is a lot.

152
00:12:57,371 --> 00:13:05,515
[SPEAKER_04]: And when I've tried to encourage other people to run for school committee, sometimes they've looked at me basically and said, do you think I'm crazy?

153
00:13:10,459 --> 00:13:17,822
[SPEAKER_04]: So I just don't want anybody to underestimate the time commitment of school committee members.

154
00:13:17,902 --> 00:13:22,444
[SPEAKER_04]: To our guests, Nia, I was on the school committee, as you can probably tell.

155
00:13:24,125 --> 00:13:28,287
[SPEAKER_04]: So anyway, okay, as we move on.

156
00:13:30,073 --> 00:13:32,314
[SPEAKER_04]: Eunice, you had asked that question about the time commitment.

157
00:13:33,654 --> 00:13:36,095
[SPEAKER_04]: In my 32 years, there was only one.

158
00:13:36,195 --> 00:13:37,636
[SPEAKER_04]: So that was 16 elections.

159
00:13:38,136 --> 00:13:40,677
[SPEAKER_04]: Only one out of 16 had nobody running.

160
00:13:41,257 --> 00:13:49,540
[SPEAKER_04]: On the other hand, I do know that there were times, including where we really sort of had to drum up interest in running for school committee.

161
00:13:49,900 --> 00:13:57,663
[SPEAKER_04]: And that's not been unusual that there are times when, you know, in the end, people end up committing, but sometimes

162
00:13:58,803 --> 00:14:00,865
[SPEAKER_04]: seems a few months ahead of time that there isn't.

163
00:14:00,885 --> 00:14:02,447
[SPEAKER_04]: Depends.

164
00:14:03,828 --> 00:14:04,709
[SPEAKER_04]: Eunice, any other thing?

165
00:14:04,909 --> 00:14:05,710
[SPEAKER_04]: Or Aubrey?

166
00:14:07,071 --> 00:14:12,836
[SPEAKER_01]: I think that's it for now until we get to, you know, the larger discussions.

167
00:14:13,557 --> 00:14:13,857
[SPEAKER_06]: Okay.

168
00:14:14,438 --> 00:14:23,326
[SPEAKER_06]: So next- My only question was about Brianna's suggestion about combining words, but I can save all those kinds of questions for when we have that conversation.

169
00:14:24,246 --> 00:14:24,426
[SPEAKER_04]: Right.

170
00:14:24,587 --> 00:14:35,042
[SPEAKER_04]: I thought when we did the pros and cons that we document that I'm suggesting that that's exactly where we're going to put those things in.

171
00:14:35,663 --> 00:14:35,763
[SPEAKER_04]: OK.

172
00:14:37,298 --> 00:14:38,839
[SPEAKER_04]: That was my vision, so to speak.

173
00:14:39,979 --> 00:14:45,721
[SPEAKER_04]: Next interview, which was an interview that I did with former school superintendent Roy Belson.

174
00:14:47,682 --> 00:14:53,705
[SPEAKER_04]: He and I sat down and chatted for quite a while just for some background information.

175
00:14:54,445 --> 00:15:03,409
[SPEAKER_04]: Roy Belson served as the superintendent of the Medford Public Schools from 1995 to 2018, one of the longest serving superintendents in Massachusetts.

176
00:15:04,149 --> 00:15:11,897
[SPEAKER_04]: Prior to that, he served initially as a substitute, a teacher, a program administrator, and then worked in central administration.

177
00:15:12,498 --> 00:15:15,421
[SPEAKER_04]: Roy grew up in Medford and attended the Medford Public Schools.

178
00:15:15,921 --> 00:15:20,086
[SPEAKER_04]: He continues to live in Medford with his wife, Maxine, who was a teacher.

179
00:15:20,626 --> 00:15:24,751
[SPEAKER_04]: Roy remains interested and involved in educational matters across the state.

180
00:15:25,985 --> 00:15:30,709
[SPEAKER_04]: So the first thing we discussed was really the role of the mayor on the school committee.

181
00:15:31,910 --> 00:15:37,434
[SPEAKER_04]: And Roy gave some background information, which may or may not.

182
00:15:37,494 --> 00:15:42,558
[SPEAKER_04]: There's one key piece which sort of explains why he feels so strongly.

183
00:15:43,298 --> 00:15:48,927
[SPEAKER_04]: So back in the days with ed reform in 1993, the role of the school committee became more established.

184
00:15:49,447 --> 00:15:52,532
[SPEAKER_04]: School committee was responsible for policy.

185
00:15:52,752 --> 00:15:58,841
[SPEAKER_04]: Administration was responsible for operations and personnel, with just a few exceptions.

186
00:15:59,938 --> 00:16:08,583
[SPEAKER_04]: Prior to that, in 1982, Proposition 2 1⁄2 took effect, which meant that the school committee no longer had fiscal autonomy.

187
00:16:09,164 --> 00:16:18,770
[SPEAKER_04]: Instead, the chief executive officer, who at that time was a city manager, would set the bottom line for the school committee, subject to the approval of the city council.

188
00:16:19,570 --> 00:16:26,954
[SPEAKER_04]: The city council could cut the bottom line of the school budget, but not add to the school budget, and that continues to this day.

189
00:16:27,935 --> 00:16:30,616
[SPEAKER_04]: Prior to that, the school committee set their budget number.

190
00:16:31,456 --> 00:16:53,380
[SPEAKER_04]: The first year that two and a half goes into effect, the then city manager cut the school budget substantially by $3.2 million, which would be equivalent to maybe $10 million today, but cut the school department, but not the city side.

191
00:16:54,260 --> 00:17:02,192
[SPEAKER_04]: This had an incredible impact on the Medford public schools for years with a huge number of teacher cuts.

192
00:17:03,402 --> 00:17:04,763
[SPEAKER_04]: Fast forward to today.

193
00:17:05,724 --> 00:17:19,199
[SPEAKER_04]: If the mayor doesn't have a real stake in the school system, which is developed by the mayor's participation at school committee meetings, he feels it's easier for the mayor not to appreciate all the needs of the school system.

194
00:17:19,980 --> 00:17:24,124
[SPEAKER_04]: The mayor's attendance puts the mayor in a public setting twice monthly.

195
00:17:25,145 --> 00:17:26,285
[SPEAKER_04]: In other words, accessible.

196
00:17:26,946 --> 00:17:33,647
[SPEAKER_04]: It's really important for the person who ultimately makes budget decisions to be involved, as involved as possible.

197
00:17:34,548 --> 00:17:37,429
[SPEAKER_04]: Roy thinks that the mayor has a citywide perspective.

198
00:17:38,109 --> 00:17:42,010
[SPEAKER_04]: As the chair, the mayor is able to listen to all the comments from members.

199
00:17:42,650 --> 00:17:45,611
[SPEAKER_04]: As just one of seven, the mayor is not as accountable

200
00:17:46,884 --> 00:17:47,585
[SPEAKER_04]: in his opinion.

201
00:17:48,045 --> 00:17:54,269
[SPEAKER_04]: Also, mayor has a specific role in capital funding proposals, which includes bonding.

202
00:17:55,590 --> 00:18:02,895
[SPEAKER_04]: Also, some school costs and city services, such as health care, trash, et cetera, are funded on the city side.

203
00:18:03,335 --> 00:18:09,520
[SPEAKER_04]: And it's vital that the mayor has a full appreciation of school system needs from the municipal side of government.

204
00:18:10,360 --> 00:18:16,084
[SPEAKER_04]: The school, and now I put this as a direct quote, the school system budget is the largest single budget in the city.

205
00:18:16,504 --> 00:18:19,606
[SPEAKER_04]: So it's vitally important that the mayor be directly involved.

206
00:18:23,462 --> 00:18:26,383
[SPEAKER_04]: Next one, ward or at large.

207
00:18:27,324 --> 00:18:30,045
[SPEAKER_04]: Key to this is how large should the committee be?

208
00:18:30,745 --> 00:18:37,008
[SPEAKER_04]: More members increases the likelihood for longer meetings and possibly greater dissonance.

209
00:18:37,769 --> 00:18:39,349
[SPEAKER_04]: Every member needs to be heard.

210
00:18:39,990 --> 00:18:42,191
[SPEAKER_04]: If ward representation is desired,

211
00:18:42,731 --> 00:18:55,055
[SPEAKER_04]: then maybe combining two wards for the purposes of electing more localized school committee members would make more sense and still allow for some at-large candidates to provide an overall experience for the city.

212
00:18:56,055 --> 00:19:01,117
[SPEAKER_04]: Don't want to discourage school committee candidates who are really interested in our public schools.

213
00:19:02,214 --> 00:19:12,503
[SPEAKER_04]: Overall, Mr. Belson believes that at-large representation has worked well on the school committee in the past and might provide the greatest overall perspective for the public schools.

214
00:19:13,244 --> 00:19:16,466
[SPEAKER_04]: High school and middle schools, he pointed out, are centralized.

215
00:19:17,888 --> 00:19:19,949
[SPEAKER_04]: Three, length of term.

216
00:19:20,190 --> 00:19:22,171
[SPEAKER_04]: No particular preference for length of term.

217
00:19:22,832 --> 00:19:26,135
[SPEAKER_04]: Overall, three years might be preferable if possible.

218
00:19:27,643 --> 00:19:38,626
[SPEAKER_04]: And on the length of term, just as a reminder, the current superintendent, she really had a preference for the longer term.

219
00:19:39,526 --> 00:19:53,109
[SPEAKER_04]: When I asked Roy about that, he said that during his tenure, he was blessed with school committee members who were on, even the shorter serving school committee members tended to be on for a fairly good number of years.

220
00:19:53,209 --> 00:19:55,130
[SPEAKER_04]: So they might be on for six or eight years.

221
00:19:57,650 --> 00:20:00,151
[SPEAKER_04]: and so that he wasn't as impacted.

222
00:20:01,292 --> 00:20:01,932
[SPEAKER_04]: Term limits.

223
00:20:02,472 --> 00:20:04,493
[SPEAKER_04]: Roy says he favors experience.

224
00:20:05,073 --> 00:20:08,995
[SPEAKER_04]: Ultimately, the public has the opportunity to recognize when change is necessary.

225
00:20:10,183 --> 00:20:18,528
[SPEAKER_04]: And fifth, other, and this is a direct quote, constructive compromise must be part of the political process for the overall good of the city.

226
00:20:19,448 --> 00:20:26,793
[SPEAKER_04]: Effective government rests on having well-intentioned people working together and overcoming disagreement to find common ground.

227
00:20:28,214 --> 00:20:30,335
[SPEAKER_04]: He went on to say, you can't legislate this.

228
00:20:30,875 --> 00:20:33,237
[SPEAKER_04]: You have to encourage this through public discourse.

229
00:20:34,345 --> 00:20:39,666
[SPEAKER_04]: And he said, changing the structure does not in and of itself produce a better result.

230
00:20:40,327 --> 00:20:50,489
[SPEAKER_04]: The more important consideration is to ensure that those who run for office and get elected understand that constructive discourse is the best way to make progress.

231
00:20:52,450 --> 00:20:54,250
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay, are there any questions about that?

232
00:20:54,270 --> 00:20:57,831
[SPEAKER_03]: No, pretty straightforward.

233
00:20:58,635 --> 00:21:05,241
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, and it was very interesting to me when I read those notes, how much she and our current mayor seem to agree on a lot of things.

234
00:21:05,601 --> 00:21:05,862
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes.

235
00:21:06,382 --> 00:21:07,623
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, it was very, yeah.

236
00:21:08,344 --> 00:21:10,286
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, it was great to have this perspective.

237
00:21:10,886 --> 00:21:11,066
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

238
00:21:11,407 --> 00:21:17,552
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, so anyway, so those were the two interviews that took place in the last couple of weeks.

239
00:21:18,413 --> 00:21:24,819
[SPEAKER_04]: Now, we had feedback from two school committee members that I had followed up with.

240
00:21:26,015 --> 00:21:35,460
[SPEAKER_04]: And they are new member Aaron Olopade and Paul Rousseau.

241
00:21:36,541 --> 00:21:38,302
[SPEAKER_04]: And let me just see.

242
00:21:38,322 --> 00:21:41,404
[SPEAKER_04]: Aubrey, which one do you want to put up first?

243
00:21:43,405 --> 00:21:44,465
[SPEAKER_03]: I have Aaron's ready.

244
00:21:45,366 --> 00:21:46,847
[SPEAKER_03]: I just let him over into the meeting.

245
00:21:47,307 --> 00:21:47,787
[SPEAKER_01]: I just did.

246
00:21:47,807 --> 00:21:49,108
[SPEAKER_01]: Hi, Milda.

247
00:21:55,368 --> 00:21:57,188
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay, so she's muted.

248
00:21:57,208 --> 00:22:06,411
[SPEAKER_04]: Hi, Melva, we're here and we're up to number three on our agenda.

249
00:22:08,871 --> 00:22:15,213
[SPEAKER_04]: Aubrey is just going to put Aaron's responses up on the screen.

250
00:22:15,613 --> 00:22:16,393
[SPEAKER_05]: Great, thank you.

251
00:22:18,653 --> 00:22:19,474
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay, so

252
00:22:24,174 --> 00:22:44,011
[SPEAKER_04]: Aaron wrote in regards to term length, when it comes to monitoring educational policy and administration, you're going to think, by the way, that I set this all up, but I honestly didn't, because here he is, the next words being a three-year term for school committee members provides a balance between stability and accountability.

253
00:22:44,691 --> 00:22:55,520
[SPEAKER_04]: This length of time gives representatives enough opportunity to become acquainted with the intricacies of education governments, participate in long-term planning, and carry out significant improvements.

254
00:22:56,241 --> 00:23:04,368
[SPEAKER_04]: It also permits leadership continuity, guaranteeing that projects can be pursued over a number of years without being hampered by frequent change.

255
00:23:05,068 --> 00:23:18,039
[SPEAKER_04]: In addition, a three-year term promotes accountability because it forces members to stand for re-election on a regular basis, giving the public a chance to assess their performance and hold them responsible for their choices and actions.

256
00:23:18,720 --> 00:23:25,405
[SPEAKER_04]: This length of time creates a fair balance between stability and responsiveness in the management of the educational system.

257
00:23:25,966 --> 00:23:30,890
[SPEAKER_04]: Lengthening to four years could also be considered an option, but I feel that may be too long.

258
00:23:32,620 --> 00:23:33,300
[SPEAKER_04]: four-year term.

259
00:23:34,121 --> 00:23:43,568
[SPEAKER_04]: First of all, longer terms entail less opportunities for voters to assess and hold elected people accountable for their deeds, which may reduce accountability.

260
00:23:44,129 --> 00:23:56,779
[SPEAKER_04]: Furthermore, four years may deter prospective candidates from entering the race because such a long term may seem daunting or excessively demanding, especially for those with other obligations in their personal professional lives.

261
00:23:57,479 --> 00:24:04,585
[SPEAKER_04]: Longer terms may also make it more difficult for elected officials to respond quickly to shifting priorities and the needs in the community.

262
00:24:05,145 --> 00:24:13,212
[SPEAKER_04]: This is because they may be less willing to change direction or take on new challenges if they feel confident in their position for an extended period of time.

263
00:24:14,453 --> 00:24:15,974
[SPEAKER_04]: Three, wards are at large.

264
00:24:16,879 --> 00:24:31,552
[SPEAKER_04]: Ward representation elections usually help a city council because they guarantee that different geographic sections within the city are fairly represented, enabling council members to properly handle particular local issues and concerns.

265
00:24:32,112 --> 00:24:44,322
[SPEAKER_04]: To guarantee that members prioritize the needs of the entire school district over those of particular neighborhoods, on the other hand, I believe the school committee may continue to implement an at-large election system.

266
00:24:45,043 --> 00:24:54,087
[SPEAKER_04]: This approach promotes a more comprehensive method of educational policymaking and resource allocation that equally serves the interests of all students and families.

267
00:24:54,868 --> 00:25:10,635
[SPEAKER_04]: As our schools within the district are spread across the city, the at-large system emphasizes the importance that not only the elected officials, but all educational personnel are conscious of the needs of different neighborhoods and how that presents in the academic day for all age groups.

268
00:25:12,293 --> 00:25:13,715
[SPEAKER_04]: and four, mayor's chair.

269
00:25:14,396 --> 00:25:26,454
[SPEAKER_04]: I do not oppose the mayor being on the committee, nor do I necessarily oppose them being a voting member, but having another chairperson may offer benefits that are not currently present with the current system.

270
00:25:27,235 --> 00:25:36,781
[SPEAKER_04]: The mayor should continue to prioritize overseeing the city as a whole and resolving a wide range of municipal issues, even though they may have a stake in the city school's performance.

271
00:25:37,402 --> 00:25:45,547
[SPEAKER_04]: Ensuring that the school committee has an independent chair promotes fairness, accountability, and openness in the decision-making processes of the educational system.

272
00:25:46,746 --> 00:25:48,107
[SPEAKER_04]: Five, term limits.

273
00:25:49,008 --> 00:25:55,092
[SPEAKER_04]: Ultimately, yes, but I think the term limit question should be addressed for each respective position in our city's government.

274
00:25:55,592 --> 00:26:01,656
[SPEAKER_04]: The limit a mayor has to govern should be weighed differently than city council member, and the same is true for the school committee.

275
00:26:02,116 --> 00:26:08,200
[SPEAKER_04]: I say this because the expectations and benchmarks for a successful term will differ greatly between each position.

276
00:26:08,801 --> 00:26:14,965
[SPEAKER_04]: What those term limits are is hard to say at this time, but I believe that it should be explored further, okay?

277
00:26:16,185 --> 00:26:22,108
[SPEAKER_04]: So that's our new member and he delved deep into many of his answers.

278
00:26:23,428 --> 00:26:27,330
[SPEAKER_04]: Any thoughts or should we move on to Paul's?

279
00:26:29,051 --> 00:26:30,892
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay, next one is Paul Rousseau.

280
