00:28:14,049 --> 00:28:15,911
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes, that's what he would be referring to.

301
00:28:16,352 --> 00:28:21,457
[SPEAKER_04]: And staggered terms is not something that we have delved into.

302
00:28:21,617 --> 00:28:24,780
[SPEAKER_04]: Some communities do have staggered terms.

303
00:28:26,242 --> 00:28:31,427
[SPEAKER_04]: Right now I'm having a hard enough time trying to figure out the length of term.

304
00:28:32,654 --> 00:28:40,258
[SPEAKER_04]: And so the staggered terms is just one level of complexity that we would need to think about.

305
00:28:40,738 --> 00:28:58,307
[SPEAKER_04]: For a long time, I was thinking that staggered terms was in fact a very important thing, but I've actually kind of moved off of that personally only because it's, as I look at it historically, there has always been a majority of members who have continued on.

306
00:28:59,295 --> 00:29:01,657
[SPEAKER_04]: so in any of our elections.

307
00:29:02,377 --> 00:29:12,103
[SPEAKER_04]: We've never been left with just one person, but staggered terms is definitely something we need to now throw into the consideration.

308
00:29:13,140 --> 00:29:25,786
[SPEAKER_03]: I know when we met with the, when we had the meeting for the Memphis Public Schools and the assistant superintendent was there, we did talk about staggered terms at that time because someone had said that the superintendent of schools talked about staggered terms too.

309
00:29:26,246 --> 00:29:27,707
[SPEAKER_03]: So that has come up before too.

310
00:29:27,747 --> 00:29:29,468
[SPEAKER_03]: We just didn't do anything further with it.

311
00:29:29,508 --> 00:29:33,710
[SPEAKER_03]: We just talked, it was just brought to the attention of people and we kind of moved from it.

312
00:29:35,671 --> 00:29:38,672
[SPEAKER_04]: They countered to staggered terms from,

313
00:29:41,168 --> 00:29:51,844
[SPEAKER_04]: is one of the things that the superintendent, Dr. Maurice Edward Vincent was saying is that she didn't want to have to go through the education process every time.

314
00:29:52,745 --> 00:29:56,110
[SPEAKER_04]: So now let's say you have four year terms, but you're staggering them.

315
00:29:56,630 --> 00:30:04,100
[SPEAKER_04]: That still means that every two years, you have the potential for having to re-educate that member.

316
00:30:04,360 --> 00:30:06,863
[SPEAKER_04]: So again, just another level of complication.

317
00:30:06,883 --> 00:30:12,370
[SPEAKER_03]: But it was also stated that there would be some continuance of people on the board that didn't have to be initiated.

318
00:30:13,051 --> 00:30:14,593
[SPEAKER_03]: Right.

319
00:30:14,613 --> 00:30:15,154
[SPEAKER_01]: Right.

320
00:30:15,794 --> 00:30:23,643
[SPEAKER_01]: I also think the issue, I'm not sure where I sit with staggered terms yet I, you know, see ups and downs to it.

321
00:30:24,144 --> 00:30:28,409
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, I'm also thinking of sort of the big picture because that would apply to.

322
00:30:30,190 --> 00:30:33,452
[SPEAKER_01]: City council discussion as well, and I think we touched on that.

323
00:30:34,192 --> 00:30:36,393
[SPEAKER_01]: Maybe last week, but.

324
00:30:37,154 --> 00:30:39,655
[SPEAKER_01]: Going back to the fact that.

325
00:30:40,575 --> 00:30:44,097
[SPEAKER_01]: Whatever we come up with for this charter as a whole.

326
00:30:45,698 --> 00:30:52,461
[SPEAKER_01]: We make our decisions and then they have to go to the city council to be blessed and then the mayor to be blessed.

327
00:30:53,161 --> 00:30:57,383
[SPEAKER_01]: And then the state to be blessed and then it goes to a vote and.

328
00:30:58,653 --> 00:31:10,695
[SPEAKER_01]: as it is, we're creating a whole new thing here, you know, versus making tweaks, um, which is what, you know, we voted early on that we would just create a new charter.

329
00:31:10,775 --> 00:31:21,017
[SPEAKER_01]: So I'm kind of wondering, and I think, you know, Ron said this last week, um, you know, we decided with city council to go to ward representation.

330
00:31:21,037 --> 00:31:25,198
[SPEAKER_01]: And then we were talking about other things like the term lengths and the term limits.

331
00:31:26,807 --> 00:31:31,969
[SPEAKER_01]: if we put too much change in there, you know, there's enough change as it is.

332
00:31:32,049 --> 00:31:40,571
[SPEAKER_01]: If we put too much in there from the get go, then it, you know, that's a whole lot for all of those layers to approve.

333
00:31:41,192 --> 00:31:53,716
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm almost wondering if we make some of these big decisions and then it puts something in the charter and this is kind of a holistic thing, but,

334
00:31:56,284 --> 00:32:14,750
[SPEAKER_01]: then let the charter live for five years, see how it goes, and have some group review it in five years or six years or something, and see how it's going, and make some tweaks to it, and then have it reviewed every 10 years.

335
00:32:14,770 --> 00:32:16,450
[SPEAKER_01]: Am I making sense?

336
00:32:17,110 --> 00:32:18,911
[SPEAKER_03]: But we're just making recommendations.

337
00:32:19,903 --> 00:32:27,454
[SPEAKER_03]: These would be our recommendations based on the survey, based on information from the interviews, from the listening sessions that we've all done.

338
00:32:27,894 --> 00:32:30,478
[SPEAKER_03]: So ours are just recommendations.

339
00:32:31,339 --> 00:32:35,826
[SPEAKER_03]: And like you said, Eunice, they have to then be passed on for further approval and all that too, so.

340
00:32:36,551 --> 00:32:44,478
[SPEAKER_03]: I think one of the things that I'm becoming more and more increasingly aware of and attentive to is that what is the best for the citizens?

341
00:32:44,838 --> 00:32:48,881
[SPEAKER_03]: And one of the things that someone just said, this might become too confusing.

342
00:32:49,302 --> 00:32:50,903
[SPEAKER_03]: I think it was you, Eunice, that just said it.

343
00:32:51,303 --> 00:32:52,684
[SPEAKER_03]: It might become too confusing.

344
00:32:52,704 --> 00:32:56,528
[SPEAKER_03]: And I think one of the things we're trying not to do is make it confusing.

345
00:32:57,168 --> 00:32:59,690
[SPEAKER_03]: So that's a good point to keep in mind also.

346
00:32:59,730 --> 00:33:01,372
[SPEAKER_03]: It's a very good point to keep in mind.

347
00:33:01,392 --> 00:33:03,153
[SPEAKER_01]: We're going from zero to 1,000 in 30 seconds.

348
00:33:05,515 --> 00:33:06,256
[SPEAKER_04]: Right.

349
00:33:06,776 --> 00:33:12,620
[SPEAKER_04]: That's certainly one of the challenges for our subcommittee, which we're only going to be able to work out when we come back as a whole.

350
00:33:13,080 --> 00:33:19,584
[SPEAKER_04]: Because as we talk about each one of these things, they have to also make sense with each other.

351
00:33:21,865 --> 00:33:23,066
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, they do.

352
00:33:23,947 --> 00:33:25,428
[SPEAKER_04]: Which is certainly challenging.

353
00:33:27,298 --> 00:33:31,800
